&gt; Here&#39;s a snippet of code from one of our unit tests:
&gt;  
&gt;         try {
&gt;             ClientSBHome home = (ClientSBHome) getEJBHome( jndiName, ClientSBHome.class );
&gt;             sessionBean = home.create();
&gt;         } catch( NamingException e ) {
&gt;             fail( &quot;Cannot get Client session bean from server: &quot; + e.toString() );
&gt;         } catch( CreateException e ) {
&gt;             fail( &quot;Cannot get Client session bean from server: &quot; + e.toString() );
&gt;         } catch( RemoteException e ) {
&gt;             fail( &quot;Cannot get Client session bean from server: &quot; + e.toString() );
&gt;         }
&gt; 
&gt; All three exceptions are considered failures -- no special handling of any.  My inclination is to simplify this code by collapsing the catch blocks into one.  Comments?
&gt;  
&gt;         try {
&gt;             ClientSBHome home = (ClientSBHome) getEJBHome( jndiName, ClientSBHome.class );
&gt;             sessionBean = home.create();
&gt;         } catch( Exception e ) {
&gt;             fail( &quot;Cannot get Client session bean from server: &quot; + e.toString() );
&gt;         }

you should only catch exceptions that you expect.  For example if a 
method has to throw a &quot;CreateException&quot;, then catchin gthis exception:

    catch (CreateException e) {
       return;
    }

will solve the problem.  The other exceptions are simply caught by the 
framework.

The easiest thing to do is add a &quot;throw Exception&quot; to the method 
signature.  Read the JUnit FAQ, it&#39;s explained in detail.

another thing:
catch (Exception e) {
    fail(&quot;blah&quot; + e.toString())
}

won&#39;t give you any detail about the stacktrace.  So go figure out where 
the NullPointerException was thrown!  To solve this, you can either 
modify the signature (see above) or use the 
junitx.f.AssertionFailedError of the JUnit-addons package.  This 
exception accepts a Throwable as attribute and is 100% compatible with 
JUnit.

-Vladimir

